{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_hobson_ver01/data/sn86075250/00517178974/1930112101/0373.xml":{"full_text":"A\nConstructive\nNewspaper\nTWENTY-SEVENTH YEAR\nHARLEM HONS AGREE\nGET DATAON FLOOD\nAREAS OF DISTRICT\nHarlem Lions had as their guests at\ntheir regular Monday evening meeting\na committee of Havre and Chinook\nbusinessmen who came down for the\npurpose of getting the club interested in\ncooperating with the Havre Chamber of\nCommerce in securing information rela\ntive to floods and flood damage in\nthis vicinity. E. C. Carruth, Frank\nCowan and Robert Lucke of Havre and\nHarry Brooks and R. V. Bottomly of\nChinook formed the visiting committee.\nArmy engineers have been investi\ngating flood damage and flood control\nin this section of Montana and making\nsurvey relative to establishing a reser\nvoir at the Chain Lakes w\u2019est of Havre.\nHowever, the various communities must\nthemselves secure data regarding dam\nages of floods, their frequency, cause\nand retention, to present to the engin\neers when they meet at Havre some\ntime in January. The Harlem Lions\nagreed to put a committee to work at\nonce to get information in the area\nextending from Madras to the Phillips\ncounty line.\nRov. W. B. Nelson of Great Falls, a\nmember of the Lions of that city, was\nalso a guest Monday night and spoke on\nLionism. Dr. W. N. Deatherage gave\na report on health and water conditions\nin Harlem. George Diveley, director of\nthe High School band, made a plea for\nassistance from the club in financing\nthe purchase of expensive band instru\nments, a bass and baritone horn for\nthe organization. Mr. Diveley asked\nthe Lions to make a loan to the band\nwhich would eventually be repaid\nthrough concerts given by the band.\nSecretary R. L. Barton read a com\nmunication from the state stockgrow\ners association asking that the club\nfollow the plan being adopted by many\nother service organizations in the state,\nthat of serving .uiontana lamb or mut\nton at one dinner each month. This\nthe Lions voted to do.\nThe club was entertained by a quar\ntet from the High School band made up\nof Volney Halsey. Reg Sundin. John\nSponenburgh and the director, George\nDiveley, playing cornets and trom\nbones.\nChristian Endeavor\nSocieties Reorganize\nThe Intermediate and Senior Chris\ntian Endeavor societies met at 5:30 and\n7 o\u2019clock, respectively, Sunday evening.\nAfter a brief devotional service, both\nsocieties held an election of officers\nfor the coming year. The results of the\nelection w T ere as follows:\nIntermediate Society\u2014President, J.\nFrank Deatherage; First vice president,\nHelen .Tones; Second vice president,\nVerna Smith; Third vice president,\nPatricia Tout; secretary, Sylvia Dol\nven; treasurer. Eunice Dolven.\nSenior Society\u2014President, Edward\nHofeldt; First vice president, Jane\nSmith; Second vice president, Oherice\nKennedy; Third vice president, Herman\nLiese; Fourth vice president, John\nJohnston; secretary, Helen Ekegren;\nTreasurer, Arnold Dolven; Music Com\nmittee, Myrtle Bergum and Marguerite\nWilson.\nChildren\u2019s Home Society\nPlans Hospital, Nursery\nIn their efforts to build a hospital\nand nursery for children of the poor in\nthis state, the Montana Childrens\u2019 Home\nSociety is making a drive to raise\n$50,000 for the necessary buildings,\nasking people of the state to purchase\nbricks at one dollar apiece for the con\nstruction of the buildings.\nPlans for the hospital and nursery\ncall for room for 30 beds for sick chil\ndren, three sunny wards, one isolation\nward and one operating room. It is\nthe plan to care for children of the\npoor absolutely free of charge while the\nparents who are able to pay will be\nasked to contribute toward the cost of\nthe care their children received. Those\nwho have means ill be urged to support\nthe children\u2019s hospital by patronizing\nit, also.\nThe cause is a worthy one and offers\na means for worthwhile Thanksgiving\nand Christmas donations.\nWins Huge Prize\nK 0\nCL I\nDr. Karl Landsteiner, bacteriologist\nand pathologist of the Rockefeller In\nstitute for Medical Research, awarded\nthe Nobel Prize in Medicine, amount\ning to more than $45,000 cash.\nTHE HARLEM NEWS\nPUBLISHED IN THE HEART OF THE FAMOUS MILK RIVER VALLEY\nBlaine Exhibitors Receive\nAwards at Seed Show\nAt the 14th annual state seed show\nand corn and potato show at Great\nFalls last week, D. C. Violett of this\ncommunity won first place with his ex\nhibit of crested wheat grass. Paul\nSpleneman of Chinook was given third\nplace by his dispaly of garden varie\nties of seed beans. William Poplar of\nZurich took fifth place with an exhibit\nof Trebi barley or other 6-row hulled\nbearded barley.\nWHAT THE RESTOF\nTHE WORLD IS DOING\nPremier Hamaguchi of Japan, was\nshot and seriously wounded by Tomeo\nSagoya, 23, a member of the reaction\nary patriotic pasty. The premier was\nshot as he w\u2019alked from the train plat\nform of the Tokyo Central station pre\nparatory to boarding a train to Okay\nama to attend annual army maneuvers,\nthe bullet entering the abdomen.\nAt the summons of the president of\nthe United States, 3,000 child health\nexperts are gathered this week at the\nnational capital in a conference on\nchild health and protection. The speech\nof President Hoover was broadcast\nover the radio Wednesday evening.\nThis is the first national conference\never called in the interest of the chil\ndren.\nThe Army and Navy football teams\nwill clash in a charity benefit game at\nNew York, Dec. 13. This is the first\ntime the two have clashed since 1927\nwhen the Army won by a score of 14-9.\nProceeds of the game this year will be\nused for the unemployed.\nBobby Jones, champion of all golf\nchampions and holder of all major tit\nles of the United States and Great\nBritain, has announced his retirement\nfrom competition. Jones has signed a\ncontract with Warner Brothers, motion\npicture firm, to make a series of 12\none-reel films, purely educational in\nnature, and says he is retiring because\nhe is convinced the contract conflicts\nwith the spirit of amateur golf rules.\nJones is but 28 years of age. He won\nhis first tournament at the age of 14.\nHowever, he did not win in a national\nmeet until 1923, at the age of 21, since\nwhen he has never been without at\nleast one championship crown.\nFred Stanek, 30 year old rural ath\nlete of lowa, shucked his way for the\nfourth time to the title of champion\ncornhusker. In the cornfield classic,\nStanek won approximately $34 for each\nof the 30.34 bushels in the victory load.\nLee Philips, Oklahoma oil man, offered\na prize of SIOOO to the w\u2019inner. News\nreel cameras and radio tower recorded\nStanek \u2019s prowess as he stalked through\nthe cornfield at Norton, Kansas.\nWinter Short Course Gives\nthe Young Man a Chance\nDo you know that the Montana State\nCollege is offering a number of practi\ncal twelve weeks short courses especi\nally for the young men from the farms\nand ranches? Here is a real opportun\nity for the young men of Blaine county\nto get some practical schooling before\nit is too late in life. Yes, Agriculture\nis coming back, but it is the young\nman who combines training with actual\nexperience who will be the farmer of\nthe future.\nHere are a few points of interest con\ncerning these courses:\n1. the courses are given at a con\nvenient time of the year.\n2.\u2014The courses are open to anyone\nwho can read and write and is over 17\nyears of age.\n3.\u2014The state refunds the railway\nfare in excess of $15.00 in making the\ntrip.\n4.\u2014'The student may choose a course\nthat will best fit him for the Agricul\ntural work he wishes to follow.\ns.\u2014The total cost, railway fare, room\nand board, books and fees, will range\nfrom $85.00 to $145.00.\n6. \u2014A graduate nurse is employed to\ncare for minor ailments and advise stu\ndents when a physician should be em\nployed.\n7.\u2014Every facility of the Institution\nwith its experienced faculty and up-to\ndate equipment such as laboratories,\ngreenhouses, creamery, shops, machin\nery, livestock, etc., are used to make\nthe courses interesting and practical.\nIt trains men to become more useful\ncitizens, better farmers and to fill im\nportant jobs in industries allied to\nfarming. Blaine county has hundreds\nof young men who would profit by at\ntending.\nTheo. Fosse, Blaine county agent, or\nJ. O. Tretsven, Principal, Bozeman,\nwill be glad to communicate with any\npersons interested.\nFive-Day Open Season\non Pheasants Near at Hand\nBlaine hunters will be allowed to kill\npheasants during a five-day open sea\nson, beginning Sunday, Nov. 23, and\ncontinuing until. Thursday, Nov. 27.\nThe birds which were planted in this\ndistrict about five years ago have in\ncreased rapidly and at the request of\nsportsmen, the open season was allowed\nby the state game board.\nThe bag on pheasants is limited to\nfive birds in the possession of a hunt\ner at one time. The birds are very\nplentiful, in spots, and every hunter of\nthe community should be able to get at\nMast one good feed of these choice\nfowls.\nHART EM, BLAINE COUNTY, MONTANA, FRIDAY, NOVEMBER 21, 1930\nThey Have Only a Feu Days to Live\nJI F T\nBus\n\u25a0-'i s AV\nFb****^ P r Fl\nL A*\"\nLm f K\nL.sl^'.\nMl\nCL vis mrL '3sl\u00ae r\nThis rural scene at the Esbenshade turkey Tarin at Ronks, Pa., is dupli\ncated in thousands of places as preparations for Thanksgiving Day arc\nmade. Perhaps the sight of Miss Edith Cromwell, feeding them their last\nmeal, may reconcile the gobblers to their fate.\nBoy Scouts Plan Winter\nCamp in Belt Mountains\nGreat Falls.\u2014There is still room for\nabout 30 Boy Scouts from the North\nCentral Montana council in the list of\nthose who will attend the third annual\nwinter camp of the council. It will be\nheld Dec. 26, 1930, at Camp Henry\nHall Johnson in the Belt mountains, it\nwas said here recently by R. D. Cook,\nScout executive. The camp is limited\nto 57 scouts.\nMr. -Cook, with Russel Conklin, field\nexecutive for the north central council,\nwill be in charge of the camp this\nyear. Frank Savage of Neihart will be\ncook, a position he filled last year.\nTo be eligible to attend, Scouts must\nbe at least 13 and must have passed all\nfirst class tests. They may come from\nany of the towns in the council where\ntroops are organized, including Havre,\nLewistown, Shelby, Conrad, Choteau,\nDutton, Chinook, Harlem, Fort Benton,\nCascade, Belt and Great Falls.\n4 \u2018l believe our winter camp is one\nof the safest that could be conducted\nanywhere,\u2019\u2019 Mr. Cook said. 4 \u2019The camp\nis just a few yards from the railroad\nso that boys may take all the bedding\nand equipment they want. There is a\nphone at the camp and a ranger station\nnearby. The Scouts will sleep in heat\ned cabins on spring cots.\nSports planned include skiing, skat\ning on Belt creek, sn^w football and\nsnowball fights. There will be a camp\nfire program each night. At the end\nof the period scouts will elect the best\ncamper. This honor went to Clayton\nLupton of Lewistown in 1928 and to\nCloyde Rockstead of Great Falls last\nyear.\nThe cost of the camp is $4.50 not in\ncluding railroad fare, but a special\nround trip rate from Great Falls will\nbe granted. Many towns in the council,\nthrough various organizations, have re\nserved places for the camp and are con\nducting contests to determine which\nScouts shall go.\nNOTICE TO NEWS PATRONS\nThe Harlem News will go to press on\nWednesday next week, owing to\nThanksgiving Day, Thursday, Nov. 27,\nbeing a holiday. All news items and\nadvertising material should be in the\noffice no later than Tuesday noon next\nweek.\nRed Cross Drive Now On\nThe Red Cross Roll Call Drive is now on in\nHarlem. Within the coming few days you will be\ncalled upon to renew your membership or to add\nyour name to the list of Harlem members of the\nnational Red Cross. Be ready to respond when the\nwomen in charge of the drive call. The dues are sl,\nhalf of which is kept in the local fund for home use.\nThe other half goes to the national headquarters\nwhere it is used in the funds ffor national relief. You\ncan do more general good with your dollar given\nthus to charity, than in any other way. If you have\nenjoyed reasonable prosperity during the past year,\ngive your dollar to this worthy cause, for this year\nthere will be more demands than usual upon the\nRed Cross.\nHarlem women, members of the Theatre-Arts\nClub, have volunteered to assist the local Red Cross\ncommittee by making a house-to-house canvass be\nfore Saturday evening. You will be called upon but\nonce, so be ready to join when you are asked. The\nwomen who are making the roll call drive are Mrs.\nSundin, Mrs. Carnegie, Mrs. Washington, Mrs.\nMinugh, Mrs. Tout, Miss Miriam Kreider, Miss Col\nlette McKenty and Miss Doris Curry.\nAssistant County Agent\nAppointed to Richland\nTheodore Fosse, serving as county\nagent of Blaine county at the present\ntime, has been appointed county agent\nof Richland County, according to an\nannouncement by J. C. Taylor, director\nof the Montana Extension Service.\nThe appointment is effective December\n10, 1930.\nMr. Fosse was appointed assistant\ncounty agent June, 1930, and stationed\nin Teton county during the absence of\nRobert E. Clarkson who took advanced\nwork at the University of Wisconsin\nlast summer. Mr. Fosse is now serving\nin Blaine county during the absence of\nMax Legge, who is acting as Montana\nManager of the Intermountain Live\nstock Marketing Association.\nMontana is Mr. Fosse\u2019s native state.\nHe was born and raised on a farm near\nFromberg and graduated from the\nFromberg High School. He attended\nMontana State College, specializing in\nlivestock and educational subjects, and\ngraduated March 31, 1926.\nDuring the rest of that year he\ntaught Smith-Hughes work at Sweet\ngrass county high school in Big Timber.\nFrom then until last June he was\nSmith-Hughes instructor at Polson high\nschool. Mr. Fosse did outstanding\nwork at Polson, having, at one time,\n60 boys taking project work. He was\nlivestock manager of the community\nfair there and was very active in com\nmunity affairs.\nWhile Mr. Fosse will cooperate with\nthe Richland County Fair, he will not\ntake an active part in the management.\nThis arrangement was made because\nthe Richland County Fair has grown\nto such, proportions that full time man\nager is necessary.\nJoe: \u201cHow were your grades last\nquarter?\u2019\u2019\nCollege: \u201cJules Verne.\u2019\u2019\nJoe: \u201cHow\u2019s that?\u2019\u2019\nCollege: \u201cTwenty thousand leagues\nunder the C.\u201d\nMistress \u2014But why did you leave\nyour last place?\nCook\u2014\u2019Cos Mr. Groucher used to\nhave such awful rows with his wife.\nMistress\u2014What did they quarrel\nabout?\nCook\u2014The way the meals was cooked.\nDairy Specialist to Meet\nBlaine Dairymen Monday\nA dairy meeting will be held Mon\nday, November 24, at 2 p. ni. in the\ncounty agent\u2019s office at Chinook for\nthe purpose of discussing dairy prob\nlems such as feeding for economical\nmilk production, the possibility of\nstarting a cow testing association and\nany other problems concerning dairy\ning that you may bo interested in.\nJ. O. Tretsven, dairy specialist from\nthe state college, will be present to\nlead the discussion on any of the prob\nlems you would like to have discussed.\nNEWS OF INTERESTING\nSTATE HAPPENINGS\nRichard Carroll, traveling salesman,\ngoes on trial at Lewistown, Dec. 2,\ncharged with first degree murder, ac\neussed with killing Stewart Shepard by\ninflicting fatal injuries with a base\nball bat after a party held last summer\nwhen Shepard got the best, of Carroll\nin a fist fight. Carroll, not realizing\nhis blows to Shepard had been fatal,\nleft the following day on a business\ntrip, but surrendered several days later\nw\u2019hen the news reached him. Both men\nwere well known in Lewistown.\n300 men started work this week on\npreliminary activities connected with\nthe building of the big power dam on\nFlathead river near Polson. The crew\nwill work eight hours a day and seven\ndays a week. Actual work on. the dam\nwill not start until spring.\nMiles City wil be host to the Class B\nhigh school football game on Thanks\ngiving day. Poplar defeated Chinook\nfor honors in this district and Harlow\nton took first place in the southern dis\ntrict, so Poplar and Harlowton will\nplay at Miles City. The Butte Purples\nand The Custer Cowboys will play for\nClass A honors at Butte the same day.\nThe trial of Anna B. Arnot of Glas\now, charged with the murder of her\nhusband on Aug. 17, has been set for\nDecember 17 or 18. Mrs. Arnot has\nbefw confined to a Glasgow hispitnl\nwhere she has been under guard since\nher illness compelled her to be moved\nfrom the county jail. Her condition is\nreported to be improved.\nMontana is asked to join with Idaho\nin the donation of a tract of land for a\nmemorial to Sacajawea, Indian woman\nguide of Lewis and Clark. It is sug\ngested that the tract be at Lemhi Pass,\nthe point where the explorers\u2019 diary\nshows the native leader was reunited\nwith members of the tribe from which\nshe was kidnapped as a child. The\nI). A. R. societies of Montana and\nIdaho are fostering the movement to\nestablish a park at this point.\nAfter waiting twenty years for her\nhusband\u2019s return, Mrs. Dermot Carter\nof Helena is filing suit for divorce.\nHer hsuband failed to return to her and\nher three children nt supper time one\nevening and has never been heard from\nin the 20 years, so Mrs. Carter thinks\nhe\u2019s gone for good and asks for legal\nfreedom.\nOutdoor Work Suspended\nby Arrival Heavy Snowfall\nThe weather for the week ending\nSaturday, November 15, 1930. accord\ning to the weekly report of Frank A.\nMath, Meteorologist of the weather bu\nreau at Havre, was fair and mild the\nfirst two days. A snowstorm set in on\nTuesday, Nov. 11, and continued moder\nately heavy for three days. Six inches\nof snow on ground Friday cold wave\nSaturday. Most outdoor work suspend\ned.\nhere was an average deficiency in\ntemperature of 3.5 degrees as compared\nwith norma.'. The highest temperature\nfor the week was 60 degrees on Mon\nday, the 10th., and the lowest was 11\ndegrees below zero on November 15,\nmaking the absolute weekly range 71\ndegrees.\nThe highest temperature for the cor\nrespondin period taken from 50 years\no< -record was 72 on November 11, 1894\nand the lowest for the same period was\n21 degrees below zero on Nov. 13, 1916.\nThe total precipitation for the week\nwas .82.\nThere w\u2019ere 5 cloudy days. 1 clear\nday and 1 partly cloudy day. The dura\ntion of registered sunshine was 24.3\nout of the 65.2 hours the sun was above\nthe horizon, making 38 percent of pos\nsible sunshine.\nThe sun rose at the end of the week\nat 7:29 a. m. and set at 4:39 p. m., mak\ning the length of day 9 hours and 10\nminutes.\nThe wind force was moderate to\nstrong with the prevailing direction\nfrom the northeast. The highest veloc\nity was 28 miles per hour from the\nsouthwest on the 11th.\nXydas\u2014l woke up in the night and\nfound my wife going through my pock\nets.\nYazge\u2014What did you do?\nXydas\u2014l turned over in bed and\nlaughed.\nVitamin \u2014Have you heard that Ga\nzoos is on the rocks?\nHormone\u2014No. What was he sent to\njail for? \u2014The Pathfinder.\nNew Stenog\u2014Sharpleigh called about\nhis account this morning.\nDunn-Brown \u2014And you told him I\u2019d\njust left for Europe?\nNew Stenog\u2014Yes, and that you\nwouldn\u2019t he back till this afternoon.\nThe Pathfinder.\nA\nConstructive\nNewspaper\nNUMBER 48\nSCOOT BENEFIT WILL\nCLOSE SOCCESSFUL\nTRADE REVIVAL WEEK\nHarlem merchants, in general, ex\npressed themselves, Thursday, as being\npleased with the outcome of their er\ntorts in making this a business revival\nweek. All business houses of the city\ncooperated in offering special values to\nthe public during the week and as a\nresult have enjoyed a brisk patronage.\nCustomers, too, have found that Har\nlem stores arc offering to them standard\ngoods at as low or lower prices than\nthey expected and where possible are\ntaking advantage of the week\u2019s himm\u2019,-\nials in laying in supplies that will be\nneeded in the days to come.\nEach afternoon at three a live tur\nkey has been set free from the second\nlanding of the Scheflow elevator, its\ncaptor becoming the orncr. Glonn\nSadler nabbed the first bird, Norman\nMcGuire caught the second and Jim.\nHarvey got the one on Wednesday. An\na grand prize, a Holstein cow is to be\nawarded to the holder of the lucky\nnumber Saturday night. The numbers\nare given away with every dollar cash\npurchase at all business places. Any\none is eligible to win, except members\nof the families of the Lions Club, who\nis sponsoring the movement, and busi\nness men who arc cooperating with thn\nplan. The drawing will take place at\nthe Scout benefit dance Saturday eve\nning.\nAh a closing feature of the week, the\nLions will hold a benefit dance Satur\nday evening at Legion Hall, proceeds to\ngo to the Boy Scout fund. Harlem Anew\nwill furnish the music and a general\ngood time is assured all who attend lu\nconnection with the dance a \u201cwhite\nelephant\u2019\u2019 auction sale will be conduct\ned for the benefit of the Scouts, al*o 9\nDonations for the sale will be solicited\nfrom every homo in Harlem, Saturday,\nafternoon when Boy Scouts will call to\nget your donations. The sale will bo\nlots of fun and well worth attending\nthe dance to see. Auctioneer A. J. Ras\nmussen has agreed to erv the sale.\nTwenty Eight Girls Report\nfor Scout Membership\nTwenty eight Harlem girle, ranging in\nage from ten to fourteen, reported bint\nWednesday after school for Girl Scout\nmembership, and all are now busy pre\nparing to take their tenderfoot testa,\ntho passing of which will entitle them\nto become registered Girl Hcouts. The\nmovement, which is new in Harlom, ia\nbeing sponsored by tho American Le\ngion Auxiliary, who has a troop com\nmittee appointed to cooperate with the\nScout lenders.\nMiss Miriam Kreider will act as the\nScout Captain. Miss Kreider, who in\na member of the. Lincoln School faculty,\nis well qualified for her position as\ncaptain, in that she has hud experience\nwith Girl Reserves and in organizing\nand conducting Nature Clubs. Who will\nbo ably assisted in her w r ork by two\nlieutenants, Miss Collette McKenty and\nMiss Blanche Dearoy, both teachers in\nour local schools. Miss McKenty han\nhad experience in Camp Fire Girls work\nwhile Miss Dearey holds a college cer\ntificate qualifying her for a Girl Scout\nleadership won through special work in\ngirl activities. Harlem is indeed for\ntunate to have such young women to\ntake charge of the new organization\nwhich promises to fill a much needed\nplace in our girls\u2019 social life.\nA Girl Scout troop may consist of up\nto forty members. Under the leader\nship of the three officers, the twenty\neight girls who enrolled last week have\nbeen divided into three troops as fol\nlows: Miss Kreider leads Alice Low\nellan, Evelyn Peterson, Loretta De\nweese, Ruth McCann, Hylvia Dolven,\nMargaret and Sydne Trethewcy, Mary\nBurton, Jennie Lee Kneedler and\nTheresa Bergum; Miss Dearey leads\nGertrude Sadler, Patricia Tout, Thelma\nPeters, Geraldine Moran, Dorothy\nDodge, Verna Smith, Helen Gwaltney,\nHelen Jones and Lettie Yelland; Mise\nMcKenty b ads Eleanor Billmayer, Eu\nnice Dolven, Erma Sherrod, Lois Fo\ngarty, Esther NorDerg, Hazel Birdwell,\nMarie Wuttke, Wilma Peters and Clara\nTurney The girls were assigned to\ntheir troops by \u201ccounting out\u2019\u2019 so that\neach group is made up of various aged\ngirls from different grades and differ\nent cliques. Friendly and profitable\nrivalry is the aim of each group. Knob\ntyjng holds the center of interest at the\npresent time. The regular meeting time\nwill be Thursday, after school.\nChamp in Court\nI I 'wl I l\n\\i\nGene Tunney, heavyweight world\nchampion, photographed in court as he\ntestifies in Tim Mara\u2019s suit against\nhim for a quarter bf his earnings.","height":"23512","width":"17116"}}
